Sure, here's how I implemented it for my side project: ```rust fn get_friendly_trait<T>(obj: &dyn Trait) -> Result<String> {
    let id = std::mem::transmute::<_, T>(obj);
    return match id {
        TypeId::of::<Vec<i32>>() => Ok("vectors are great".to_string()),
        _ => Err(format!("not a vec: {:?}", obj)),
    };
}
```
The `transmute` macro is the big performance killer here. Without it, we'd just call `obj.method()!`. I had to keep writing raw casts every single time I used trait objects because of this overhead.

